There is no interest from his side to hold elections this year, because he wants to stay in power.The opposition wants Kabila to end his 15-year rule in December as mandated by the constitution but authorities say the vote cannot be held until at least next July, and the top court has said Kabila can stay in power until the election is held. The government of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has rejected fresh demands from the opposition that elections be held and President Joseph Kabila step down by December 20 of this year.

Political tensions are high in Congo before a scheduled November presidential election. President Joseph Kabila, in power since 2001, is required by the constitution to step down this year but the government says logistical and budgetary constraints make it unrealistic to hold the election on time.

@Intriligator: @Intrilligator: Constitutional court 11 May ruled that President Kabila could legally stay in office after his second term ends in Dec if elections have not been held. Main opposition parties rejected judgement, called for protest marches. Anti-govt protests held throughout country 26 May, clashed with police in several cities, one protester and one policeman killed in Goma. Ex-Katanga Governor Moïse Katumbi 4 May said he would run in presidential elections; govt same day opened investigation into Katumbi’s alleged hiring of foreign mercenaries in plot against govt. Prosecutor general 19 May issued arrest warrant for him but Katumbi flew with prosecutor’s permission to South Africa 20 May for medical treatment, 27 May flew to Europe. Attacks on civilians rose in eastern Beni territory, North Kivu, attributed to Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) rebels, leaving at least twenty people dead; armed forces 14 May launched new operation against ADF.

«DR Congo risks 'even worse crisis' over Kabila uncertainty: ... 'Tensions rose further when the country's Constitutional Court ruled in May [1] that Kabila could remain in a caretaker capacity beyond December until elections are held. The strongman's supporters want elections, due later this year, to be delayed for two to four years. No date has yet been set for the polls. Last month, opposition parties forged an alliance to demand Kabila quit his post in December, warning that him staying on would be tantamount to a "constitutional coup d'etat". » [2] [1] «Following the principle of continuity for the state and to avoid a lack of head of state, the current president remains in office until the installation of a newly-elected president," said the Constitutional Court statement read by its head, Benoit Luamba Bintu. The court was responding to a request to clarify the matter.» http://www.france24.com/en/20160512-drcongo-court-joseph-kabila-mandate-presidential-elections [2] https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/31963943/dr-congo-risks-even-worse-crisis-over-kabila-uncertainty/#page1

Now this is interesting: http://www.africanews.com/2016/06/20/drc-gov-t-directs-internet-service-providers-to-restore-tariffs/ Rather than shutting down the Internet, as happened last year, the government has decided to simply price it out of the reach of most citizens. This follows recent (unconfirmed) reports that more than 100 higher education institutions have been closed since late last year. If you wanted to minimize the chances of an uprising over, say, postponed elections, this would be a pretty good way to do it.

If Kabila continues to insist on the electorial reforms AND the census that would be needed for them, there is just no way to get this done in time. In fact, this make take several more months and may easily derail into 1-2 years. The only reason why I am not at 99% at NO is that he might not care too much over the quality of the census. Then again: This is probably nothing more than a stalling tactic and he might use the objective difficulties in conducting a census as such. As long as there is no legal way for him to take office for a third term, he will want to sit this out. I am unsure if he can amend the consitution in time and he doesn't seem too eager to get this done in time anyway. Maybe he is speculating that at some point the majority will be fine with an amendment of the constitution as long as they get any elections?

There is no requirement, either in this Q or in the real world, that these elections must comply with either the legal norms of the DRC or the standards of common decency. The Kabila family are not noted for their commitment to legal processes or even, as above, common decency. If I'm Joe, I brush aside the niggling domestic, constitutional, and international objections and open the polls, at the same time asking people to lift that pesky term limit. I win, to the surprise of let's say nobody.

how many times have we seen this story? The elections almost never proceed. If they do, it will be in 2017. Between arresting his opponent, amending the constitution and military crackdowns, even if there are sanctions it will likely only result in an announcement of elections, but not actual elections in 2016. The sham governors elections give him more of a hold on resources and localities, enough so that he can hold them "hostage." It is difficult to see a) he will go without a fight and b) that will happen in 2016.

When the incumbent seeks to modify the constitution to seek an extra term, that's never a sign that elections will proceed as planned. The violence that has plagued Burundi has been caused in large part due to that country's president seeking a third term. Either way, this suggest Kabange will use extra legal means to attempt to ensure his hold on power. So, either there will not be elections (likely), or the elections will be held, but in a way to ensure Kabange will win.

In recent decades it has been felt necessary by incumbent autocrats to have elections, preferably featuring either rigging or grievous bodily harm. Kabila knows this and will likely have some sort of elections, the results of which will be widely and correctly disbelieved. Stay tuned.

After doing a little more reading, including the piece at the link below, I am betting heavily on the election not happening in 2016. If it does happen this year, though, I expect it will be under conditions that are less favorable to Kabila (which is a big part of why they are likely being delayed in the first place), so I see Katumbi as the favorite in that scenario.
